You are right, I don't mean "abstract HTML", I just mean to provide a way to generate it from code using the same syntax of your code. This is what I use:<p><a href="https://github.com/antirez/lamernews/blob/master/app.rb#L1388" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/antirez/lamernews/blob/master/app.rb#L138...</a><p>For instance to write<p><pre><code>    <foo>
      <bar id="4">content</bar>
    </foo>
</code></pre>
You write:<p><pre><code>    H.foo {
        H.bar(:id => 4) {"content}
    }
</code></pre>
So everything you can write in HTML you can write in this DSL, there is no real abstraction, but it is Ruby code like in all the rest of the application.
